th, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Checkenden, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1198–Abt October 1246":"1198–circa oktober 1246","1198–1246":"1198–1246","1201–1273":"1201–1273","1206–1273":"1206–1273","1229–1266":"1229–1266","1215–Female":"1215–Overleden","–1250":"–1250","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1160–Female":"1160–Overleden","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1206":"1206","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1201":"1201","1266":"1266","1155":"1155","Abt October 1246":"circa oktober 1246","about 1255":"circa 1255","BEF. 1228":"vóór 1228","1229":"1229","Checkenden,Oxford,England":"Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England","Tamworth, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni":"Tamworth, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Checkenden, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1198–Abt October 1246":"1198–about October 1246","1198–1246":"1198–1246","1201–1273":"1201–1273","1206–1273":"1206–1273","1229–1266":"1229–1266","1215–Female":"1215–Deceased","–1250":"–1250","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1206":"1206","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1201":"1201","1266":"1266","1155":"1155","Abt October 1246":"about October 1246","about 1255":"about 1255","BEF. 1228":"before 1228","1229":"1229","Checkenden,Oxford,England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England","Tamworth, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni":"Tamworth, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Checkenden, Oxfordshire, England":"Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marmion","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: perhaps an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name. Compare   Merriman  .","English (Lancashire; of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Old French <i>marmion</i> ‘monkey, brat’."],"variants":[{"name":"Merriman","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>mirie</i>, <i>merie</i>, <i>murie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Merry   1. This surname is established in Ireland (perhaps as an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name; compare   Marmion  ) as well as England.","there has probably been some confusion with <b>Marriman</b>, probably an occupational name meaning ‘servant of <i>Mary</i>’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’, or perhaps a pet form of <i>Mary</i> using the hypocoristic suffix -<i>man</i>. The surname <i>Marriman</i> is now vanishingly rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marmon","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Gloucestershire):","variant of   Marmion  .","variant of <b>Marriman</b>, an occupational name meaning ‘servant of Mary’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’."]}]},{"name":"Geoffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":17,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":26,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Geoffrey Marmion was born in 1198, in Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Marmion Lord of Checkenden, was 43 and his mother, Mrs William MARMION, was 39. He married Mrs. Rosamund Marmion before 1228, in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died about October 1246, in his hometown, at the age of 48, and was buried in Checkendon, Oxfordshire, England."},"et":{"1198–Abt October 1246":"1198–umbes oktoober 1246","1198–1246":"1198–1246","1201–1273":"1201–1273","1206–1273":"1206–1273","1229–1266":"1229–1266","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","–1250":"–1250","1155–1220":"1155–1220","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1206":"1206","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1201":"1201","1266":"1266","1155":"115